03945nmm a2200589Ia 9781501742507DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20191979nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017425077 a10.1515/97815017425072doi  a(DE-B1597)567518  a(OCoLC)1241099131  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aDC146.L204a944/.035/09241 aLafayette, Le Marquis de, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLafayette in the Age of the American Revolution—Selected Letters and Papers, 1776–1790 :bApril 10, 1778–March 20, 1780 /cLe Marquis de Lafayette; ed. by Mary Ann Quinn, Linda J. Pike, Roger E. Smith, Stanley J. Idzerda. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2019] 4c©1979  a1 online resource (520 p.) :bPhotos, maps, chart  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Lafayette Papers0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe second volume in this distinguished series provides a comprehensive picture of the Franco-American alliance and of the day-to-day problems of conducting the War of Independence as reported by Lafayette and his correspondents on both sides of the Atlantic.Volume II begins with Lafayette's reunion with the main army at Valley Forge in the spring of 1778, after an assignment to Albany. It follows him on his return to France in January 1779, on leave from the American army, and ends in the spring of 1780, when he was sent back to America to announce the coming of the French expeditionary force and to help formulate American plans for cooperation with the French forces.Complementing Lafayette 's personal memoirs, which open the two parts of the book, are exchanges of letters with such prominent figures as George Washington1 Henry Laurens, Benjamin Franklin, the Comte d'Estaing, John Paul Jones, and the Comte de Vergennes. The documents and letters written in English are published as they appear in the manuscripts; those written in French appear both in the original and in translation.Much of the basic material for this series, which will comprise six volumes, is drawn from Lafayette's own collection of manuscripts. A brilliant portrait of Lafayette in his own words, the books reveal much more complex elements in his character and outlook than have been apparent before.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 4aLiterary Studies. 4aU.S. History.1 aIdzerda, Stanley J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPike, Linda J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aQuinn, Mary Ann, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSmith, Roger E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150174250740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501742507423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501742507/original  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles